05404nam a22008775i 9783110643930DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20192020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106439307 a10.1515/97831106439302doi  a(DE-B1597)512818  a(OCoLC)1132424128  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0042502bisacsh04a930215  aGW 5790qDE-25/sred202rvk0(DE-625)rvk/45457:1 aMales, Mikael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Poetic Genesis of Old Icelandic Literature /cMikael Males. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (VIII, 353 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aErgänzungsbände zum Reallexikon der Germanischen Altertumskunde ,x1866-7678 ;v11300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Note on Translations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Metre and Rhyme -- t2. Diction: Mythology, Wordplay, Metaphor and Tmesis -- t3. Grammatical Literature -- t4. Prosimetrical Narrative -- t5. Poetry, Language and Snorri’s Edda in the Mid-Fourteenth Century -- t6. Conclusions -- tAppendix: Texts by the Wormianus Redactor -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book assesses the importance of poetry for the Old Icelandic literary flowering of c. 1150–1350. It addresses the apparent paradox that an extremely conservative form of literature, namely skaldic poetry, was at the core of the most innovative literary and intellectual experiments in the period. The book argues that this cannot simply be explained as a result of strong local traditions, as in most previous scholarship. Thus, for instance, the author demonstrates that the mix of prose and poetry found in kings’ sagas and sagas of Icelanders is roughly contemporary to the written sagas. Similarly, he argues that treatises on poetics and mythology, including Snorri’s Edda, are new to the period, not only in their textual form, but also in their systematic mode of analysis. The book contends that what is truly new in these texts is the method of the authors, derived from Latin learning, but applied to traditional forms and motifs as encapsulated in the skaldic tradition. In this way, Christian Latin learning allowed for its perceived opposite, vernacular oral literature of pagan extraction, to reach full fruition and to largely replace the very literature which had made this process possible in the first place.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aOld Norse literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aOld Norse poetryxHistory and criticism. 4aAltisländische Literatur. 4aSkaldendichtung. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Scandinavian.2bisacsh  aOld Icelandic literature.  askaldic poetry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE  DG 2019 Englishz978311061685908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishz978311061036908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2019z9783110606348oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831106423770 cprintz978311064183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311064393040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110643930423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110643930/original  a978-3-11-061036-9  EBOOK PACKAG